Capstone project: Data-driven suggestions for HR¶

Description and deliverables¶

This objective is to analyze the dataset and build predictive models that can provide insights to the Human Resources (HR) department of a large consulting firm.

Deliverables include the model evaluation and interpretation, a data visualization(s), ethical considerations, and the resources used to troubleshoot and find answers or solutions.

Business scenario and problem:¶

The HR department at Salifort Motors wants to take some initiatives to improve employee satisfaction levels at the company: what’s likely to make the employee leave the company?

If you can predict employees likely to quit, it might be possible to identify factors that contribute to their leaving. Because it is time-consuming and expensive to find, interview, and hire new employees, increasing employee retention will be beneficial to the company.

HR dataset dictionary¶

Variable |Description | -----|-----| satisfaction_level|Employee-reported job satisfaction level [0–1]| last_evaluation|Score of employee's last performance review [0–1]| number_project|Number of projects employee contributes to| average_monthly_hours|Average number of hours employee worked per month| time_spend_company|How long the employee has been with the company (years) Work_accident|Whether or not the employee experienced an accident while at work left|Whether or not the employee left the company promotion_last_5years|Whether or not the employee was promoted in the last 5 years Department|The employee's department salary|The employee's salary (U.S. dollars)

source on Kaggle.

# convert departments into ordinal var
def dept_to_ordinal(df_cleaned):
    depts=df_cleaned["department"].unique()
    print(depts)
    dept_ord={}
    for ix,i in enumerate(depts):
        dept_ord[i]=ix
    print(dept_ord)
    df_cleaned["dept_ordinal"]=df_cleaned["department"].apply(lambda x:dept_ord[x])
    return df_cleaned

# Determine the number of rows containing outliers
iqr_all={}
for col in df_.columns:
    
    data = df_[col]
    if data.value_counts().count() > 2 and data.dtype!="O":
        iqr = data.quantile(.75) - data.quantile(.25)
        upper_lim = data.quantile(.75) + iqr * 1.5 
        lower_lim = data.quantile(.25) - iqr * 1.5
        outliers = ((data<=lower_lim)|(data>=upper_lim)).sum()
        # export outlier data?
        #outliers_df = data[data > lower_lim & data < upper_lim]

Helper Function: Hypothesis Testing¶

In [17]:
def hypocheck(col_list,aliases):
    col_alias= {col:alias for (col,alias) in zip(col_list,aliases)}
    for col in col_list:
        pval=stats.ttest_ind(
            a=df_left[col],
            b=df_stay[col],
            equal_var=False
            )[1]
        print(f"It is {str(pval<0.05).lower()} (at p-value {pval:.3}) that employees' likelihood towards {col_alias[col]}s differs based on their choice to leave or stay.")

#make data split
def split_data(X,y):
    x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,train_size=0.6,random_state=42,stratify=y)
    x_test,x_val,y_test,y_val=train_test_split(x_test,y_test,train_size=0.5,random_state=42,stratify=y_test)
    for i in [x_train,x_val,x_test]:
        print(i.shape)
    print(X.shape)
    return x_train,x_val,x_test,y_train,y_val,y_test

Evaluate Model Performance¶

In [32]:
def get_metric_name(metric):
    return f"{metric}".split("=")[0].replace("<function","").split("at")[0].strip()
In [33]:
def eval_model(model,model_name,results_df=pd.DataFrame(),show_cm=False):
    """
    Takes a model, its name/description, and a dataframe.
    Returns a dataframe with evaulation results, option to display a confusion matrix.
    """
    eval_results = {}
    eval_results["model_name"] = model_name
    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
    for metric in [metrics.accuracy_score,metrics.precision_score,metrics.recall_score,metrics.f1_score]:
            eval_results[get_metric_name(metric)]=[round(metric(y_test,y_pred),3)]
    if show_cm:
        cm= metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred,labels=model.classes_)
        disp= metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm,display_labels=model.classes_)
        disp.plot()   
        plt.title(f"{model_name} Confusion Matrix")
        plt.show()
    return pd.concat([results_df,pd.DataFrame(eval_results)],axis=0)
